Cluster comparison w.r.t. some indicators of study habits

Compare the clusters of the 4 cluster model with respect to the following variables:

  • week_prop_sd - standard deviation (SD) of weekly session proportions (weeks 6 and 13 are excluded)
  • weekday_prop_sd - SD of weekday session proportions (weeks 6 and 13 are excluded)
  • ses_timegap_mad - Median Absolute Deviation (MAD) of the time gap (measured in minutes) between consecutive study sessions
  • on_topic_prop - proportions of on-topic or preparation sessions; computed as the ratio of the number of sessions with the main topic being the weeks topic and the total number of sessions of the given student (weeks 6 and 13 are excluded)
  • on_topic_prop_sd - SD of on-topic proportions computed at the weekly level (weeks 6 and 13 are excluded)
  • last_min_prop - the proportion of on-topic (preparation) sessions done in 24h before a weeks lecture (weeks 6 and 13 are excluded)
  • last_min_prop_sd - SD in the weekly proportions of last minute preparation sessions

Load the indicators

indicators <- read.csv("Intermediate_results/regularity_of_study/regularity_indicators.csv")
# keep only the above listed indicators
indicators <- indicators %>%
  select(user_id, week_prop_sd, weekday_prop_sd, ses_timegap_mad, 
         on_topic_prop, on_topic_prop_sd, last_min_prop, last_min_prop_sd)
# merge indicators with cluster assignments
clust.data <- merge(x = indicators, y = cluster.assignments[,-2], 
                    by = 'user_id', all.x = FALSE, all.y = TRUE)

Pair-wise comparisons of clusters with Mann-Whitney U Test

pairwise.compare <- function(indicator, clusters, cl1, cl2) {
  indicator.cl1 <- indicator[clusters == cl1]
  indicator.cl2 <- indicator[clusters == cl2]
  do.Mann.Whitney.test(indicator.cl1, indicator.cl2, cl1, cl2)
}
pairwise.compare.clusters <- function(indicator, clusters, ncompare) {
  nclust <- length(unique(clusters))
  comparison <- matrix(nrow = ncompare, ncol = 5, byrow = T)
  k <- 1
  for(i in 1:(nclust-1)) {
    for(j in (i+1):nclust) {
        comparison[k,] <- c(i, j, pairwise.compare(indicator, clusters, i, j))
        k <- k+1
    }
  }
  comparison.df <- as.data.frame(comparison)
  colnames(comparison.df) <- c('c1', 'c2', 'Z', 'p', 'r')
  comparison.df <- apply.FDR.correction(comparison.df)
  comparison.df
}

Cluster comparison w.r.t. the daily resource use statistics

Comparison of student clusters based on some basic statistics about the different kinds of resources students used during their active days (an active day is a day when a student had at least one study session). The types of resources considered:

  • video (VIDEO)
  • exercises (EXE)
  • multiple choie questions (MCQ)
  • reading materials (RES)
  • metacognitive items (METACOG)

Computed statistics:

  • median_X_cnt - median number of resources of type X used during the students active days (X can be VIDEO, EXE, MCQ, RES, METACOG)
  • mad_X_cnt - MAD (median absolute deviation) of resources of the type X used during the students active days
  • days_X_used - number of days when resources of the type X were used
  • prop_X_used - proportion of days when resources of the type X were used versus total number of the students active days

Weeks 6 and 13 were excluded from the computation of the above statistics, as during these weeks one can expect different than usual pattern in the resources use.

Load the resource use stats and merge with the cluster assignments:

Cluster comparison based on resource use on particular week day

daily.res.counts <- read.csv("Intermediate_results/regularity_of_study/daily_counts_of_resource_use_w2-13.csv")
count.vars <- colnames(daily.res.counts)
## remove columns related to weeks 6 and 13
weeks_6_13 <- grep("^(W6|W13).+", count.vars)
count.vars <- count.vars[-weeks_6_13]
daily.res.counts <- daily.res.counts %>% select(one_of(count.vars))
## load cluster assignments
cluster.assignments <- read.csv("Intermediate_results/regularity_of_study/regularity_based_clusters.csv")
weekday.res.counts <- function(res.counts) {
  weekday.counts <- matrix(nrow = nrow(res.counts), ncol = 9)
  s <- 1
  for(stud in res.counts$user_id) {
    stud.weekday.cnt <- vector(mode = 'numeric', length = 9)
    stud.weekday.cnt[1:2] <- c(stud, res.counts$cl4[s])
    
    stud.data <- res.counts %>% filter(user_id==stud) %>% select(2:71)
    
    for(d in 1:7) { # 7 days in a week
      weekday.cnt <- 0
      for(w in 0:9) {# 10 weeks
        weekday.cnt <- weekday.cnt + stud.data[d + w*7]
      }
      stud.weekday.cnt[2+d] <- as.numeric(weekday.cnt)
     # print(stud.weekday.cnt)
    }
    
    weekday.counts[s,] <- stud.weekday.cnt
    s <- s + 1
  }
  
  weekday.counts.df <- data.frame(weekday.counts)
  colnames(weekday.counts.df) <- c('user_id', 'cl', 'Sun', 'Mon', 'Tue', 'Wed', 'Thu', 'Fri', 'Sat')
  weekday.counts.df
}

Create a box plot for each cluster

boxplot.weekday.counts <- function(weekday_long) {
  require(gridExtra)
  
  g.cl1 <- ggplot(weekday_long %>% filter(cl==1), aes(x=weekday, y=weekday_cnt, fill=weekday)) + geom_boxplot() + ggtitle("Cluster 1") + theme(legend.position="none")
  
  g.cl2 <- ggplot(weekday_long %>% filter(cl==2), aes(x=weekday, y=weekday_cnt, fill=weekday)) + geom_boxplot() + ggtitle("Cluster 2") + theme(legend.position="none")
  
  g.cl3 <- ggplot(weekday_long %>% filter(cl==3), aes(x=weekday, y=weekday_cnt, fill=weekday)) + geom_boxplot()+ ggtitle("Cluster 3") + theme(legend.position="none") 
  
  g.cl4 <- ggplot(weekday_long %>% filter(cl==4), aes(x=weekday, y=weekday_cnt, fill=weekday)) + geom_boxplot() + ggtitle("Cluster 4") + theme(legend.position="none")
  
  grid.arrange(g.cl1, g.cl2, g.cl3, g.cl4, ncol=2, nrow=2)
}

Cluster comparison w.r.t. the daily topic focus

Comparison of student clusters based on some basic statistics about the different kinds of topics student actions were associtated with during their active days (an active day is a day when a student had at least one study session). The following topic foci were considered:

  • ontopic - the topic associated with a learning action is the topic of the current week
  • revisiting - the topic associated with a learning action is the topic of one of the previous weeks
  • metacognitive - the topic associated with an action is one of the following: ORG, DBOARD, STRAT, STUDYKIT
  • orientiring - the topic associated with an action is one of the following: HOME, HOF, SEARCH, TEA, EXAM, W01-W13
  • project - a learning action is related to project work

For each student and each day during weeks 2-5 and 7-12, counts of learning events / actions with the above given topic foci were calculated. So, for each student and each day, we have the number of learning actions that were ontopic, number of actions that were revisiting and so on.

The computed statistics:

  • median_X_cnt - median number of learning actions associated with topic X during the students active days (X can be ontopic, revisit, metacog, orient, prj)
  • mad_X_cnt - MAD (median absolute deviation) of the number of learning actions associated with topic X during the students active days
  • X_days - number of days with at least one learning action associated with topic X
  • X_prop - proportion of days with at least one action on topic X versus total number of the students active days
